@node Systemvoraussetzungen "PacMan.Guide: System requirements"
@prev About
@next Benutzung

PacMan runs with Kick 1.2 or higher.
PacMan can't be run from workbench, it's also unuseful.
Some RAM for crunching/decrunching could be helpful...

Additional files used by PacMan:

AmigaGuide.library:   Used to make you read this text.
Decrunch.library:     will always be needed.
Powerpacker.library:  is needed to crunch files.
Reqtools.library:     only needed when password crunching/decrunching.
@endnode

@node About "PacMan.Guide: General description"
@prev Main
@next Systemvoraussetzungen

PacMan is a crunch/decrunch tool using the decrunch.library. The library
is part of the virus killer VirusZ by Georg Hörmann. It recognizes a
stately number of cruncher types.

PacMan works basicly like the well-known DLD, but with PacMan some useful
extra-options are coming around.

PacMan can show up the uncrunched length of a crunched file without
decrunching it first (fine when viewing only), but it knows only a few
cruncher types (and only reloc/data header crunchers).
PacMan.CrList shows up their names.

Note: i'm still searchin' for the crunchers in this list, which are marked
with a question mark (reloc/data type only).

After decrunching PPData-files, the .pp suffix will be cut off.

Absolute crunched programs can be saved as executables after depacking.

After that, PacMan can crunch data-files via powerpacker.library.
So, the PPData-cruncher/decruncher will no longer be needed.

Note: PPData-files will always be decrunched with the decrunch.library,
because the powerpacker.library is not 100% bug-free and could produce
damaged files (but this will be rare).
@endnode

