@node Benutzung "PacMan.Guide: How to use"
@prev Systemvoraussetzungen
@next Modi

PacMan can't be started from Workbench.

CLI: run PacMan as follows:

PacMan [-<Opts>] <Mode> <FileName>

@{" Mode " link "Modi"} determines what PacMan shall do with <FileName>.
This may be: crunching, decrunching or just examining it.

@{" Opts " link "Opts"} are optional arguments specifying special options
while processing the file/directory.

Note: case doesn't matter anywhere in the command line. 
The filename never need to be quoted, even if it contains any spaces.

A destination name doesn't need to be specified. PacMan always saves the
destfile with a different name than the source's one and kills the source
file only after successful saving of the destfile (if you wish so).
This is called "safe saves".

Anyone who knows how to extract the PacMan archive with LhA, knows how to
use PacMan, too. See also: @{" examples " link "Beispiele"}.
@endnode

@node Beispiele "PacMan.Guide: Usage examples"
@prev Benutzung
@Next Copyright

PacMan -T-6 -N -E D RAM:PackedFile

Decrunch a file named "PackedFile".

-T-6  PacMan will run with a tsak priority of -6.
-N    The original file will not be deleted after successful depacking.
-E    The file won't be decrunched, if it's not executable (just data).

Another way to pass the args:

PacMan -PNR1 C DH0:BigTextFile

Crunches a file via PowerPacker.library.

-P    The file will be crypted using a password.
-N    The original file won't be deleted after successful decrunching.
-R1   The file will be recrunched with "BEST" efficiency, if...
      ...see also: @{" crunch options " link "OptsC"}.
@endnode

@node Modi "PacMan.Guide: modes"
@prev Benutzung
@next Opts

PacMan awaits one of these three modes: C, D or V.

C   Crunch file. This option indicates that PacMan has to crunch the spe-
    cified file via powerpacker.library.
    There are no PP standard options for crunching, because I think they
    are unnecessary.
    The crunch buffer will always be set to largest size, if there's
    enough RAM available. If you worry about that, go to a computer-shop
    and buy some more RAM.
    Crunching efficiency will be set to "BEST". Decrunching PPData-files
    will always take the same time with all efficiencies.

    PacMan will never take over the power-led.
    I hate such programs...

    A .pp-suffix will be added to the destination name.

    (If this is impossible, PacMan will cut the last three chars of the
     filename and add the suffix .pp. If the filename is 30 chars long and
     ends with .pp, the destfile will get the suffix .p2.)

    If the sourcefile is already crunched (which is checked before attemp-
    ting to crunch), PacMan stops trying to crunch it.

    Note: PacMan will skip executable files. Why should it crunch programs
    as data files ?

D   Decrunch file. Will decrunch the specified file.

    The destfile gets the suffix .bin. If not possible (see crunch file),
    PacMan changes the suffix to .new.

  After successful saving, PacMan deletes the Sourcefile and renames the
  destfile to the original name.

  The suffix .p2 on PPData-files will be changed to .pp (if necessary),
  after deleting the sourcefile.

V   View file. Examines the file and shows the information about the used
    cruncher. This will also show up the cruncher type (A,R,D).

    R means, the file is packed fine with a real cruncher.

    A means, some dude used a fucking lame absolute code cruncher.
    Crunchers like those are trashł. They decrunch a file to a specific
    RAM address. Those tools see no reason to check if the needed memory
    block is already allocated. That means: frequent system-crashes.

    D shows up that the file is a crunched data-file.
@endnode

@node Opts "PacMan.Guide: Optional arguments"
@prev Benutzung
@next OptsC

For every @{" work mode " link "Modi"} special extra options hang around to change some
parameters from default to your wishes.
The arguments do not match on every work mode. Every mode has it's own op-
tional argument set.

These are: @{" crunch options " link "OptsC"}, @{" decrunch options " link "OptsD"} and @{" view options " link "OptsV"}.
@endnode

@node OptsC "PacMan.Guide: Crunch options"
@next OptsD
@prev Opts

-K   Keep source protection bits. With this option you can cause PacMan to
     copy the protection bits of the original file to the destination
     file. The only exception is the archive bit, which will never be set.
     With this option, you may protect yourself against accidently dele-
     ting the crunched file or something like that. If you make use of
     these protection bits, this option may make a sense for you.

-Mnn Set minimum crunch efficiency. You may specify a minumum percentage
     gain for crunching files. If a file was crunched with a lower gain,
     it won't be saved and the original file stays as it is.
     nn is a decimal value between 0 (nonsensical) and 99 (nonsensical,
     too :^).
     There's no need to type a leading zero if the value is smaller than
     10.
     By the way: the default minimum value is 15.

-N   Never kill sourcefile. The source-file will not be deleted after
     saving the destination file, if this option is given.

-O1  Other progress display 1. This is an alternate display type of the
     crunch process. PacMan displays a kind of countdown instead of the
     normal display, where the number displayed first is the length of the
     sourcefile. Then, the number of crunched bytes will be subtracted
     continuos till zero. 
     I think this looks more clear.

-O2  Other progress display 2. The third display method is a percentage
     type output, which indicates how many percent of the file have been
     crunched.

-P   Password crunch. You know about that. This will crypt the file with a
     password, so that the destfile is protected absolutely uncrackable.
     -if you beleive that...:^)

-R1  Recrunch file. Every PPData file which is not packed "BEST" will be
     depacked and crunched with "BEST" efficiency, if this option is se-
     lected.

-R2  Recrunch always. If selected, every crunched datafile will be de-
     crunched and then crunched with "BEST" efficiency. That means, PacMan
     will decrunch data files of any packer type.
     Notice that R2 recrunches everything (except executables).

-S   Crunch small files. Normally, PacMan doesn't crunch files smaller
     than 513 bytes, because you won't neither save disk space nor loading
     time. If you have a reason to crunch such mini-files, select opt -S.

-Tn  Set taskpri. PacMan everytime sets it's task priority to -1, preven-
     ting the CPU from freezing your system too much. PacMan ignores the
     priority of the CLI task it was launched from.
     If you wish to change PacMan's taskpri, add the -T option.
     Values between -9 and 9 are allowed.
     Any blanks between T and the desired value are not allowed.
     Examples: -T2 or -T-6.

-V   Verify writes. This option lets PacMan completely load the destina-
     tion file directly after saving. If an error occurs, PacMan aborts
     any action, so that the original file won't be killed anymore. Useful
     for people who don't call a harddisk their own.

-X   Crunch executables. This option is only given to the freax, who make
     use of the PPLoadSeg tool. If you don't have got a harddisk, this op-
     tion may be interesting for you....

Opt -X cannot be used together with -R1 or -R2.
@endnode

@node OptsD "PacMan.Guide: Decrunch options"
@next OptsV
@prev Opts

-B  Save A-file as RAW binary image. Normally, PacMan saves A-type files
    as executables after decrunching.
    If the decrunched file shall be saved as RAW data file, opt B must
    be used. 

-D  Data files only.

-E  Executables only. Good for decrunching big games for quicker hd-
    loading.
    Doesn't touch data-files, 'cause some bad coded games await their
    data files in crunched state.

-K  Keep source protection bits. This is the same as -K in crunch mode.

-N  Never kill sourcefile. The source-file will not be deleted after sa-
    ving the destination file. PPData-files without the .pp-suffix will
    get the suffix .bin.

-Tn Set taskpri. See @{" crunch opts " link "OptsC"}.

-V  Verify writes. See @{" crunch opts " link "OptsC"}.

-Y  Save A-file as reanalyzable object. Well, I'll need a few more words
    to explain this function...
    Normally, PacMan generates a Loader for decrunched A-files, which
    checks out if the desired absolute RAM block is free.

    If not, the program will finish properly. An error message will not
    be displayed. In this case, nothing will happen except that the CLI
    prompt reappears. An error message would make the loader unnessecary
    longer (132 bytes code...).

    There are two different kinds of PacMan-generated loaders.

    Some kinds of absolute crunchers can save a programm with a "kill
    system decruncher". A such decrunch header switches off the operating
    system before starting the program. This will give the programm full
    CPU capacity and the ability to access the full available RAM size.

    PacMan automaticly distinguishes those decruncher types and generates
    a kill system loader for these programs. This one doesn't need
    to check if the needed absolute RAM block is free (code length: 92
    bytes).

    By chance, I found a program which was crunched twice; a program,
    which was crunched and the crunched one then was crunched again.
    PacMan could never recognize the second decruncher, because the de-
    crunched file will normally be saved with PacMan's loader and checking
    that file again would fail.

    So, to completely decrunch this file, the Y option comes around.
    If used, PacMan doesn't add a loader to the destination file. It only
    saves it as a pure executable file.
    This file mustn't ever be run, because it will crash everytime.
    AmigaDOS will load the file into any RAM block which is free at the
    moment, but surely not exactly to the right address.

    If PacMan can't identify this file, the original must be decrunched
    again without opt Y.

    If PacMan recognizes the second (...,third, fourth...) cruncher of
    that file, than you can decrunch it without opt Y and finally you will
    get a well running executable.

    Again: opt Y is only used for checking an absolute packed file for
    further decrunchers.

    Dont' forget to use opt N with opt Y...

    Another thingy: don't change the file comment of a file decrunched
    with opt Y, because PacMan saves an information ahere, which declares
    if the file has to be saved with a kill system loader after decrun-
    ching it a second time, when (one of) the first decruncher(s) was a
    kill system decruncher.

Notes:

    The decrunch routines of A-files mostly don't test if the needed abso-
    lute RAM block is free. It's recommendable to decrunch those files
    ALWAYS. These files may be crunched again with a proper cruncher
    (PowerPacker, CrunchMania, Imploder...).

    However, PacMan's loader is no warranty for proper running programs
    which don't cause damage to your system.
    Such programs often don't think about running system-friendly, even
    like it's crunchers, too...

    Save all important RAM data to disk before running such programs.
    After it has finished, you should reset your system, if your Amiga
    didn't already walk to India.

    Important:
    ----------

    The loaders generated by PacMan don't think about checking if there's
    a workbench message waiting which has to be replied when finishing the
    task, because PacMan doesn't know if the decrunched program already
    checks this itself. This would cause a system crash.

    That means: do not run A-type files from workbench. There's no dif-
    ference between running the crunched or the decrunched program; the
    decrunchers of absolut packed files never check if they were run from
    workbench.
    An illegal workbench launch causes damage and chaos to your system
    which is not recognized by the user everytime. But a crash is not far
    away...

    By the way: PacMan itself also doesn't check if it was launched from
    workbench, because it's written ONLY for usage from CLI or tools like
    Directory Opus.

    For password crunch/decrunch, the ReqTools.library is needed.

You mustn't select option D together with opt B, E or Y. This will
cause PacMan to shriek off an error text.
Also not allowed is opt B together with opt Y.
@endnode

@node OptsV "PacMan.Guide: View options"
@next Beispiele
@prev Opts

-Tn Set taskpri. Not very interesting in view mode. See @{" crunch opts " link "OptsC"}.

In View mode (and only here) you may also specify a path instead of a
filename (e.g. DH0: or BBS/Doors).
In this case, every entry in this directory will be examined and the re-
sults will be displayed on the screen.
While viewing a path, PacMan switches it's text outputs to a QuickView
mode, where only name (of the entry), cruncher type and cruncher name will
be displayed. This is because now all information can be displayed in a
single line to give the text outputs a bit more clearness.

For viewing complete directories, there are some further opts. If you
specified a filename instead of a path, PacMan doesn't stop it's activi-
ties, but these opts then will be ignored.

-C  Collect sub-directories recursively. This one is not implemented by
    now, but it'll be included in one of the next versions, as soon as
    possible; because you need to switch off the fuction of that name in
    DirOpus to get use of the new QuickView mode and/or higher processing
    speeds while checking complete directories.
    In future, this one will check every sub-directory of the specific
    path recursively.

-H  Hide directories. With this option you can suppress sub-directories to
    be displayed to make the text outputs smaller.
    (This one only works if opt C isn't selected, of course.)

-Q  Switch QuickView mode off. If you want all extra informations on files
    being displayed, you may select this option. Normally, the QuickView
    mode is turned on everytime you specify a path.

-U  Hide uncrunched files. Like opt H, this option suppresses uncrunched
    files to be displayed. This is very useful if you only want to know
    which files in the selected directory are crunched.

In QuickView mode, absolute crunched files will be highlighted.
@endnode

@node Anmerkungen "PacMan.Guide: Special notes"
@next Sonstiges
@prev Copyright

I have analyzed several KillSys decrunchers of different cruncher types.
These differ a bit from one another, but PacMan's KillSys loader is nearly
100 % compatible with all of them.

If a KillSys program of a specific cruncher doesn't run, I will fix this,
of course.
However, I only made a few tests with that.

PacMan will be updated whith new versions of the decrunch.library, if the
library was expanded by new functions.

P.S.: sorry for my kewl schewl english. :^)


              PacMan !  -spread the disk, not the word !
@endnode

