PacMan now can save A-type files as executables.

Opt A killed. It's no longer necessary.

Added B option.

Added Y option.
@endnode

@node V114 "PacMan.Guide: Changes in version 1.14"
@next V115
@prev V113

Painful: by accident, I smashed the wrong PacMan version into the V 1.13
archive. This one wrote a rubbish text on the screen after crunching a
file. This was for testing PacMan...
The correct version of PacMan is 11204 bytes long and writes "V 1.13" on
the screen, 'cause this additional archive only contains the PacMan file
and is not a complete update.
@endnode

@node V113 "PacMan.Guide: Changes in version 1.13"
@next V114
@prev V112

PacMan now displays load/jump addresses of a decrunched A-type file.

The new decrunch.library recognizes 5 more cruncher types (see
PacMan.CrList). -PacMan now knows, too.

Bug fix: V 1.12 already displayed a (rubbish) destination length for those
files at preview, although they weren't implemented.

Optimized code a bit.
@endnode

@node V112 "PacMan.Guide: Changes in version 1.12"
@next V113
@prev V111

Fixed a harmless bug (mistaken error message).

Fixed another bug: a crunched file may be longer then the uncrunched one,
if the source file is very small (approx. 20-60 bytes).
In this case, the powerpacker.library doesn't return any error, because
it doesn't consider that the real destination length will be 8 (passworded
files: 10) bytes longer when saved.
PacMan crashed when calculating the "gain" percentage (division by zero
error)...

After all, crunching files smaller than 513 bytes will never profitable,
'cause AmigaDOS always takes 512 bytes for saving the data part of a file,
even then the file is e.g. only 70 bytes "long".
Beyond that, you'll loose loading time, because decrunching of the file
needs time, too...

Therefore, PacMan will not crunch any file smaller than 513 bytes.
Only if you've selected...

the new -S option.

Added -Tn option (set taskpri).
PacMan now always runs with a task priority of -1, no matter which prio-
rity is given to the CLI task it was launched from.
If you want to change that, use the -T option.

Added -X option.

Added -O1 and -O2 option.

Added usage info.

Included the newest ReqTools.library.
@endnode

@node V111 "PacMan.Guide: Changes in version 1.11"
@next V112
@prev V110

PacMan now displays the pack efficiency of any PPData file.

Added two new recrunch opts: -R1 and -R2 (bug free, I hope...)

Text output improved.

Fixed a very stupid bug while displaying the version number on the screen.
PacMan printed one (fortuitous) char too much...:^)
@endnode

@node V110 "PacMan.Guide: Changes in version 1.10"
@next V111
@prev V100

Important: the command line parser was rewritten.
PacMan now awaits the arguments in a standard format like LhA does.

Bug fix: if an error occured while decrunching a file (e.g. out of mem),
PacMan went on a world trip with India as first station...

The version number inside the program is crypted now.
(Fight fucking lame fakers !)

A password crunch option was added (-P).
@endnode

